NAME
    termcap(3)		- routines to read the termcap file

SYNOPSIS
    int tgetent( buffer, name )
      char  buffer[ 1024 ];
      char *name;

    int tgetflag( entry )
      char *entry;

    int tgetnum( entry )
      char *entry;

    char *tgetstr( entry, p )
      char *entry;
      char **p;

    char *tgoto( cm_string, column, line )
      char *cm_string;
      int   column;
      int   line;

    tputs( string, count, Putchar )
      char *string;
      int   count;
      void  (*Putchar)();

DESCRIPTION
    To read a termcap description into memory, use tgetent().
    The capabilities of the terminal "name" will be copied
    to the "buffer". This buffer is used by tgetflag(), tgetnum()
    and tgetstr().

    This routine checks the $TERMCAP string in the environment,
    using the following algorithm,

      if ( $TERMCAP is undefined ) then
        search file /etc/termcap for "name"

      else if ( $TERMCAP starts with a '/' ) then
        search file $TERMCAP for "name"

      else if ( $TERM = "name" ) then
        use $TERMCAP as the termcap

      else
        search file /etc/termcap for "name"

    Note this means that when $TERM is changed $TERMCAP must be
    either updated or removed, see tset(1).

    On successful completion tgetent() returns 1. If it can not
    open the termcap file then -1 is returned. If there is no
    description for "name" then 0 is returned.

    READING ENTRIES

    To check for the presence of an entry in a description, use
    tgetflag(). This routine returns 1 if the capability is 
    present, 0 if not and -1 for invalid calls.

    The "co" and "li" entries have a numeric value. A numeric
    entry is read by tgetnum(). If the entry is not specified
    then -1 is returned.

    Most entries are strings, and are read by tgetstr(). If
    the requested entry is found, then it is copied to **p.
    *p is incremented by the size of the entry. A pointer to
    the start of the string is returned if successful, NULL
    is returned if the entry was not found.

    GENERATING OUTPUT

    To position a cursor on the screen the routine tgoto() is
    used. This takes the "cm" string and a column and line
    number, and forms a string which can be sent to the terminal
    by using tputs(). If tgoto() encounters a problem, then the
    returned string is "OOPS". There are some special format
    commands recognized by tgoto(), see termcap(4) for details.

    All strings returned by tgetstr() or tgoto() should be
    output using tputs(). This performs the appropriate padding
    for different terminals under various Unix systems.
    For Minix, tputs() simply calls "Putchar()" for each
    character in "string".

    NOTES

    XTABS should be off while using termcap(3).

    See termcap(4) for a complete description of the termcap 
    entries and the escape codes available for use within strings.


FILES
    /etc/termcap	The termcap entries

SEE ALSO
    termcap(1), tset(1), termcap(4)

BUGS
    tgetent() only checks the second terminal name in a description.

    tgoto() does not use BC or UP to avoid unpleasant characters.

    tgoto() is missing some format commands, including "%r".

    tputs() does not do padding under Minix.
